{"title_page": "Set You Free (album)", "text_new": "{{About|the Gary Allan album|other albums|Set You Free (disambiguation){{!}}Set You Free}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Set You Free\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Gary Allan]]\n| cover      = Gary Allan - Set You Free.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{start date|2013|01|22}}\n| recorded   = 2012-2013\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]]\n| length     = 46:13<ref name=ALL/>\n| label      = [[Universal Music Group Nashville|MCA Nashville]]\n| producer   = {{Hlist|Gary Allan|[[Greg Droman]]|[[Jay Joyce]]|[[Mark Wright (record producer)|Mark Wright]]}}\n| prev_title = [[Icon (Gary Allan album)|Icon]]\n| prev_year  = 2012\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Set You Free\n | type        = Studio\n | single1     = [[Every Storm (Runs Out of Rain)]]\n | single1date = September 17, 2012\n | single2     = [[Pieces (Gary Allan song)|Pieces]]\n | single2date = February 25, 2013\n | single3     = [[It Ain't the Whiskey]]\n | single3date = September 23, 2013\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Set You Free''''' is the ninth studio album by American country rock artist [[Gary Allan]]. It was released on January 22, 2013, by [[MCA Nashville]].,<ref>{{cite news|last=Duvall|first=Erin|title=Gary Allan, 'Set You Free' Track List, Album Art Revealed|url=http://www.theboot.com/2012/12/17/gary-allan-set-you-free-track-list/|accessdate=December 25, 2012|newspaper=The Boot|date=December 17, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Whitaker|first=Sterling|title=Gary Allan Announces Release Date, Track Listing for Upcoming Album \u2018Set You Free\u2019|url=http://tasteofcountry.com/gary-allan-set-you-free-release-date/|accessdate=December 25, 2012|newspaper=Taste of Country|date=December 18, 2012}}</ref> and is Allan's inaugural No 1. album on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart, debuting at the top spot on February 9, 2013. It is also Allan's second No. 1 album on the [[Top Country Albums]] chart, following 2005's ''[[Tough All Over (Gary Allan album)|Tough All Over]]''. The album produced three singles: \"[[Every Storm (Runs Out of Rain)]]\", \"[[Pieces (Gary Allan song)|Pieces]]\", and \"[[It Ain't the Whiskey]]\".\n\n== Background ==\n\nGary Allan talked to ''The Boot'' writer Vernell Hackett, and Allan commented on the time during making of this album was one of transition for his label. In addition, Allan noted how he worked with producers in a competitive effort to make this album better.<ref name=BOOT>{{cite web|url=http://www.theboot.com/2013/01/22/gary-allan-set-you-free-album-interview/|title=Gary Allan, 'Set You Free' Is an Emotional, Hopeful Journey|last=Hackett|first=Vernell|date=January 22, 2013|publisher=The Boot|accessdate=January 29, 2013}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|text=I recorded the album during the transition of label heads and no one realized what I was doing until I turned it in...When you have one producer, you sometimes allow a song to get in there as an album cut. But with different producers, each one is competing to have the best songs and hopefully songs that are good enough to be released as singles, so I think the overall album and the quality of songs were better because of it. I forced myself to stretch on this one, because I had time, and I think you need to do something new to keep reinventing yourself.|sign=Gary Allan|source=<ref name=BOOT/>}}\n\n;Title\n\nGary Allan talked to ''The Boot'' writer Vernell Hackett, and Allan mentioned the title came from the lead single from the album because it is what the effort as a whole is all about.<ref name=BOOT/>\n\n{{quote|text=That's like the flavor of every song on there...The whole album has hope and was timely for me, too. I've waited a long time to get back on the radio.|sign=Gary Allan|source=<ref name=BOOT/>}}\n\n;Theme\n\nGary Allan talked to ''The Boot'' writer Vernell Hackett, and Allan stated the album's songs are set to the arc of a relationship.<ref name=BOOT/>\n\n{{quote|text=When I got the songs in the order I liked I realized what I had done was create a story line so that it played like a breakup...The first song is 'Tough Goodbye,' and then I went through all the emotions of a breakup, all way to the healing song, 'Good as New.' So the album covers the gamut of a breakup and the first stages of healing.|sign=Gary Allan|source=<ref name=BOOT/>}}\n\n==Commercial performance==\nOn February 9, 2013, ''Set You Free'' was the most sold album in the United States by the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart, as well as, the most sold [[Top Country Albums|Country Album]] the same week on the charts. In addition, the album was the second most sold [[Top Digital Albums|Digital Album]], which it was the No. 13 most sold album in Canada, and this was all for this same week on the charts. As of March 6, 2013, the album has sold 219,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roughstock.com/blog/country-album-chart-news-for-march-6-2013-the-return-of-the-mavericks-emmylou-harris|title=Country Album Chart News For March 6, 2013: The Return of The Mavericks & Emmylou Harris|author=Matt Bjorke|work=RoughStock}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = (78/100)<ref name=META>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/set-you-free/gary-allan |title=Set You Free, Ratings, Credits, and More |publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=February 22, 2013}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[About.com]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=ABT>{{cite web|url=http://countrymusic.about.com/od/reviews/fr/Gary-Allan-Set-You-Free-Album-Review.htm|title=Gary Allan \u2013 'Set You Free' Album Review|last=Silva|first=Robert|date=January 22, 2013|publisher=About.com|accessdate=February 22, 2013}}</ref>\n| rev2 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=ALL>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/set-you-free-mw0002471116|title=Set You Free \u2013 Gary Allan : Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|date=January 22, 2013|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=January 29, 2013}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[American Songwriter]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=AS>{{cite web|url=http://www.americansongwriter.com/2013/01/gary-allan-set-you-free/|title=Gary Allan: ''Set You Free''|last=Conaway|first=Alanna|date=January 22, 2013|work=American Songwriter|accessdate=January 29, 2013}}</ref>\n| rev4 = Got Country Online\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=GCO>{{cite web|url=http://www.gotcountryonline.com/album-review-gary-allan-set-you-free/|title=ALBUM REVIEW: Gary Allan \"Set You Free\"|last=Block|first=Donna|date=January 20, 2013|publisher=Got Country Online|accessdate=February 22, 2013}}</ref>\n| rev5 = [[PopMatters]]\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|7|10}}<ref name=PM>{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/168211-gary-allan-set-you-free/|title=Gary Allan: Set You Free|last=Cibula|first=Matt|date=February 15, 2013|publisher=PopMatters|accessdate=February 22, 2013}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev6Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=RSM>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/set-you-free-20130128|title=Gary Allan: Set You Free (MCA Nashville)|last=Eddy|first=Chuck|date=January 28, 2013|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=January 29, 2013}}</ref>\n| rev7 = Roughstock\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=RS>{{cite web|url=http://www.roughstock.com/reviews/album-review-gary-allan-set-you-free|title=Album Review: Gary Allan \u2013 Set You Free|last=MacIntosh|first=Dan|date=January 21, 2013|publisher=Roughstock|accessdate=January 29, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130127213903/http://www.roughstock.com/reviews/album-review-gary-allan-set-you-free|archive-date=January 27, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev8 = [[Taste of Country]]\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=TOC>{{cite web|url=http://tasteofcountry.com/gary-allan-set-you-free/|title=Gary Allan, \u2018Set You Free\u2019 \u2013 Album Review|last=Dukes|first=Billy|date=January 24, 2013|publisher=Taste of Country|accessdate=January 29, 2013}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[USA Today]]''\n| rev9Score = {{Rating|4|4}}<ref name=USA>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2013/01/21/gary-allan-set-you-free/1852661/|title=Gary Allan does outlaw right on 'Set You Free'|last=Mansfield|first=Brian|date=January 22, 2013|work=USA Today|accessdate=January 29, 2013}}</ref>\n}}\nUpon its release, ''Set You Free'' received generally positive reviews from most music critics.<ref name=META/> At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[Standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the album received an [[weighted mean|average]] score of 78, based on 7 reviews, which indicates \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref name=META/>\n\nThe album has only garnered positive reviews, so far. Those came in from [[About.com]], [[AllMusic]], ''[[American Songwriter]]'', ''[[The Boston Globe]]'', ''[[Country Weekly]]'', ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', Got Country Online, ''[[The Plain Dealer]]'', [[PopMatters]], ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', Roughstock, [[Taste of Country]], and the ''[[USA Today]]''. [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] of AllMusic gave the album a three-and-a-half-out-of-five-star rating, saying that the album is \"one where all of his past is present in his assured professionalism.\"<ref name=ALL/> Likewise, ''American Songwriter'' music critic Alanna Conaway rated it the same, and wrote that \"''Set You Free'' will give his long-time followers more than they could have hoped for, while garnering new fans coast-to-coast.\"<ref name=AS/> In addition, Stuart Munro of ''The Boston Globe'' also rated it the same, which is based on [[Metacritic]]'s assigned score, and stated that \"[Allan] may offer less of an alternative than he once did, but that old-school concern and a wider sonic palette keep Allan just this side of the mainstream.\"<ref name=BG>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/music/2013/01/21/album-review-gary-allan-set-you-free/vvj7hGkGghnT3gyhuF2XnI/story.html|title=ALBUM REVIEW: Gary Allan, 'Set You Free' \u2013 Music|last=Munro|first=Stuart|date=January 21, 2013|work=The Boston Globe|accessdate=January 29, 2013}}</ref> Similarly, ''Rolling Stone'' music critic [[Chuck Eddy]] gave it the same rating as well, and evoked how \"the 45-year-old singer lets the crazy out\" on the album.<ref name=RSM/> Furthermore, Dan MacIntosh of Roughstock even gave it the same exact rating and wrote that \"Many of these song lyrics are intensely self-directed\" that are meant for \"that tragic guy at the end of the bar\" and proclaimed how the album is \"fun, but all over before you know it. Then you\u2019re back to crying away your blues.\"<ref name=RS/> Lastly, [[About.com]] music critic Robert Silva rated it the same himself, and noted how \"''Set You Free'' can use these jolts of energy, but Allan still seems at his best -- and definitely in his comfort zone -- when he's maudlin, morose, and three sheets to the wind.\"<ref name=ABT/>\n\n''The Plain Dealer'''s Chuck Yarborough graded the album a perfect A+ grade, and alluded to how \"'Set You Free' boasts of the typical Allan sound \u2013 a sort of lonesome dove lament in his voice \u2013 but there\u2019s also an in-your-face stab at belligerence called 'Bones' that runs contrary to form.\"<ref name=PD>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/popmusic/index.ssf/2013/01/gary_allans_new_set_you_free_i.html|title=Gary Allan's new 'Set You Free' is a lesson in healing from a man who knows pain (review)|last=Yarborough|first=Chuck|date=January 18, 2013|work=The Plain Dealer|accessdate=February 22, 2013}}</ref> Bob Paxman of ''Country Weekly'' gave the album an A grade and affirmed that \"''Set You Free'' doesn't sound like every other album coming out of the Nashville factory these days\u2014and that's definitely a good thing.\"<ref name=CW>{{cite web|url=http://www.countryweekly.com/reviews/set-you-free-gary-allan|title=''Set You Free'' by Gary Allan|last=Paxman|first=Bob|date=January 22, 2013|work=Country Weekly|accessdate=January 29, 2013}}</ref> Paxman went on to describe how \"[t]he album flows freely, again as the title might suggest, and the divergent styles truly complement one another.\"<ref name=CW/> On the other hand, Grady Smith of ''Entertainment Weekly'' graded the album a B+ grade, and alluded to \"how Gary Allan is beginning to let a small amount of sunshine in.\"<ref name=CW2>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20665271,00.html|title=Also Available: Gary Allan ''Set You Free''|last=Smith|first=Grady|date=January 18, 2013|work=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=February 22, 2013}}</ref>\n\nPopMatters' Matt Cibula give the album a seven-stars-out-of-ten rating and acclaimed that \"[t]his album is the truth.\"<ref name=PM/> Taste of Country's Billy Dukes rated the album even better, giving it a four-and-a-half-out-of-five. He noted how \"[e]ach track is a surprise that pays off handsomely when the time is invested.\"<ref name=TOC/> Donna Block of Got Country Online rated in a perfect five-stars and evoked how \"[i]t is said a picture is worth a thousand words,\" and saying, \"Here the lyrics sketch out what the music (and Gary\u2019s vocals) paints in bold, rich colors. Here is a mix of old and new country, blended with acceptance and hope throughout.\"<ref name=GCO/> Finally, ''USA Today'' music critic [[Brian Mansfield]] also rated it a perfect four star effort, and wrote, \"It's a hard-won hope. Brooding songs, like the one where's he's digging a grave for an unsuspecting, unfaithful love, are as scary as hell.\"<ref name=USA/> Mansfield concluded saying, \"Gary Allan has [...] lived a life that most other country acts can, well, only sing about. That's why the cracks in Allan's voice convey experience, not affection, and why he doesn't have to sing about how country he is for everyone to know.\"<ref name=USA/>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{tracklist\n| extra_column    = Producer(s)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Gary-Allan-Set-You-Free/release/6341792|title=''Set You Free''|work=[[Discogs]]|accessdate=21 March 2015}}</ref>\n| title1          = Tough Goodbye\n| writer1         = [[Josh Thompson (singer)|Josh Thompson]], [[Tony Martin (songwriter)|Tony Martin]]\n| extra1          = [[Jay Joyce]]\n| length1         = 3:14\n| title2          = [[Every Storm (Runs Out of Rain)]]\n| writer2         = Gary Allan, [[Hillary Lindsey]], Matt Warren\n| extra2          = Allan, [[Greg Droman]]\n| length2         = 3:46\n| title3          = Bones\n| writer3         = [[Keith Gattis]]\n| extra3          = Allan, Droman\n| length3         = 3:54\n| title4          = [[It Ain't the Whiskey]]\n| writer4         = Greg Barnhill, Jim Daddario, [[Cole Deggs]]\n| extra4          = Joyce\n| length4         = 4:20\n| title5          = Sand in My Soul\n| writer5         = [[The Warren Brothers|Brad Warren, Brett Warren]], [[Blair Daly]]\n| extra5          = Allan, Droman\n| length5         = 3:19\n| title6          = You Without Me\n| writer6         = Allan, John Lancaster, [[Rachel Proctor]]\n| extra6          = Allan, Droman\n| length6         = 3:55\n| title7          = One More Time\n| writer7         = Allan, Lindsey, M. Warren\n| extra7          = Joyce\n| length7         = 5:25 \n| title8          = Hungover Heart\n| writer8         = James Leblanc, M. Warren\n| extra8          = Allan, [[Mark Wright (record producer)|Mark Wright]]\n| length8         = 3:48\n| title9          = No Worries\n| writer9         = Allan, Odie Blackmon, [[Pat McLaughlin]]\n| extra9          = Allan, Wright\n| length9         = 3:18 \n| title10         = Drop\n| writer10        = Joel Shewmake, Bruce Wallace, Brian Gene White\n| extra10         = Joyce\n| length10        = 4:15 \n| title11         = [[Pieces (Gary Allan song)|Pieces]]\n| writer11        = Allan, Blackmon, [[Sarah Buxton]]\n| extra11         = Joyce\n| length11        = 3:24\n| title12         = Good as New\n| writer12        = [[Billy Burnette]], McLaughlin\n| extra12         = Allan, Wright\n| length12        = 3:35\n| total_length    = 46:13<ref name=ALL/>\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n{{div col|rules=yes|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Gary Allan]] &ndash; [[acoustic guitar]], [[electric guitar]], lead vocals, background vocals\n* David Angell &ndash; [[violin]]\n* Brian Arsenault &ndash; [[bass guitar]]\n* Matt Billingslea &ndash; [[drums]]\n* [[Tom Bukovac]] &ndash; acoustic guitar, electric guitar\n* Perry Coleman &ndash; background vocals\n* [[Chad Cromwell]] &ndash; drums\n* [[Eric Darken]] &ndash; [[percussion]]\n* David Davidson &ndash; violin\n* Levi Dennis &ndash; [[fiddle]], acoustic guitar, [[viola]], background vocals\n* [[Greg Droman]] &ndash; 12-string guitar, electric guitar\n* [[Dan Dugmore]] &ndash; [[steel guitar]]\n* Tim Galloway &ndash; electric guitar\n* [[Kenny Greenberg]] &ndash; electric guitar\n* Vicki Hampton &ndash; background vocals\n* [[Hanna-McEuen|Jaime Hanna]] &ndash; acoustic guitar, background vocals\n* Lee Hendricks &ndash; bass guitar\n* Wes Hightower &ndash; background vocals\n* [[Jedd Hughes]] &ndash; acoustic guitar, electric guitar\n* [[Jay Joyce]] &ndash; acoustic guitar, electric guitar, background vocals\n* [[Jack Lancaster|John Lancaster]] &ndash; [[Hammond B-3 organ]], [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]], [[piano]], [[Wurlitzer]], background vocals\n* [[Hillary Lindsey]] &ndash; background vocals \n* Rob McNelley &ndash; electric guitar\n* [[Marilyn Martin]] &ndash; background vocals\n* [[Steve Nathan]] &ndash; Hammond B-3 organ\n* Russ Pahl &ndash; steel guitar\n* [[Rachel Proctor]] &ndash; background vocals\n* [[Giles Reaves]] &ndash; drums, [[Fender Rhodes]], Hammond B-3 organ, percussion, piano, [[synthesizer]], [[xylophone]]\n* [[Michael Rhodes (musician)|Michael Rhodes]] &ndash; bass guitar\n* David Steele &ndash; acoustic guitar, electric guitar, background vocals\n* [[Ilya Toshinsky]] &ndash; hi-string guitar,